  "prompt": "What are the main reasons why students from Boston University don't graduate on time?",
  "response": "There can be several reasons why students from Boston University, or any university, might not graduate on time. Some common factors include:\n\n1. **Course Load and Scheduling:** Students may take a lighter course load each semester or face difficulties in getting the required courses due to scheduling conflicts or limited availability.\n\n2. **Academic Challenges:** Some students may struggle with academic performance in certain subjects, leading to the need to retake courses which can delay graduation.\n\n3. **Changing Majors:** Students who change their major may find that not all of their previously completed courses count toward their new major's requirements, extending the time needed to graduate.\n\n4. **Personal Issues:** Health issues, family emergencies, or personal challenges can impact a student's ability to maintain a full course load or perform well academically.\n\n5. **Financial Constraints:** Financial difficulties can lead to students taking semesters off to work, reducing the number of courses they can afford to take at once, or even dropping out temporarily.\n\n6. **Internships and Co-op Programs:** Participation in internships or co-op programs, while valuable for career development, can extend the time to degree completion if they do not integrate seamlessly with academic requirements.\n\n7. **Extracurricular Commitments:** Heavy involvement in extracurricular activities or athletic commitments might affect the time students can dedicate to their studies.\n\n8. **Advising and Support:** Inadequate academic advising or support might lead students to take unnecessary courses or delay fulfilling graduation requirements.\n\nWhile these are general reasons, each student's situation is unique, and multiple factors often interplay to affect graduation timelines.",
